column168: I RECEIVED A CALL FROM BOB OSBORN, SAFETY DIRECTOR FOR AKZO COATINGS/RELIAN CE, AT ABOUT 7:30AM. HE SAID HE HAD A TRUCK COMING FROM BREA TO WOODSTUFF M FG. AND THAT THE DRIVER HAD STOPPED AND WAS REPORTING A LEAK FROM UNDERNEAT H HIS TRUCK. I CALLED DISPOSAL CONTROL SERVICE AND TOLD THEM THE SITUATION. I THEN CALLE D THE DRIVER OF THE TRUCK AND GOT DIRECTIONS AS TO WHERE HE HAD STOPPED. I THEN  CALLED BACK DISPOSAL CONTROL SERVICE  AND REQUESTED  THAT THEY MEET M E AT THE SPILL SITE. I WAS THE FIRST TO ARRIVE AT THE SPILL SITE, AND BEGAN TO INSPECT THE TRUCK INSIDE AND OUTSIDE. THE TRUCK WAS CARRYING 6 TOTE TANKS FILLED WITH CLEAR LACQUER AND CLEAR LAC QUER SANDING SEALER. I RE-ENTERED THE TRUCK AND DISCOVERED THAT ON TOP OF O NE OF THE TOTES (TANK #102) MATERIAL 401-90C018-750 WAS LEAKING FROM THE TO P WHERE  THE RING WAS CLAMPED DOWN ON THE TOTE. I PRECEDED TO REMOVE  THE R ING  AND DISCOVERED NO RUBBER GASKET WAS THERE, ALSO A LARGE  WET PUDDLE OF LACQUER ON TOP OF THE TOTE AND DOWN THE SIDE. I LEFT THE LID UNSCREWED AND GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK TO GET SOME FRESH AIR. THE SPILL WAS CAUSED FROM NO GASKET AND SLOSHING AROUND BACK AND FORTH THRO UGH THE METAL BUNG AND DOWN THE SIDE. AT THIS TIME, THE DISPOSAL CONTROL SERVICE  HAD ARRIVED , AND ADVISED US TH AT WE CALL THE FIRE DEPT DUE TO THE EXTREMELY BAD FUMES AND THE HIGH RISK O F EXPLOSION. THEY ALSO ADVISED US TO CALL DEPT OF PUBLIC SAFETY. WHEN THE FIRE DEPT AND DPS ARRIVED AT THE SPILL SITE THE CONCLUSION REACHED WAS TO MOVE THE TRUCK TO ANOTHER PLACE AWAY FROM THE PRIVATE LOT THE TRUCK WAS PARKED ON. I INFORMED THAT  THE LID  I HAD REMOVED EARLIER WAS NOT  SE CURE AND THAT IT WOULD NEED SECURED BEFORE MOVING  THE TRUCK. THIS THEY DID AT THE PRIVATE  LOT WHICH WAS THE SPILL SITE. THIS WAS DONE BY THE DISPOSA L TEAM INSIDE THE TRUCK. THEY SECURED  THE TOTE TANK (#102) WITH THICK VISQ UEEN AND SCREWED DOWN THE LID. THEY THEN LET THE TRUCK AIR OUT. I THEN WENT BACK INSIDE THE TRUCK MYSELF TO GIVE THE FINAL INSPECTION. AT T HIS TIME, I HEARD A HISSING AND DRIPPING SOUND. UPON INSPECTION, I DISCOVER ED ANOTHER TOTE  THAT WAS AGAINST THE BED OF THE TRUCK, HAD A 3" CRACK ABOU T 12" DOWN FROM THE TOP ON TANK #52. MATERIAL 401-90C018-750. IT WAS BLEEDI NG , LIKE A CUT ON YOUR ARM. I CALLED THE DISPOSAL TEAM BACK INTO THE TRUCK INTO THE TRUCK. WE DISCUSSED DUMPING THE MATERIAL FROM THE TOTE INTO DRUMS, BUT THEY DECIDE D  TO PATCH  THE TOTE . WHICH THEY DID AND LET DRY FOR ONE HOUR. EVERYONE LEFT AND WE CAME BACK TO THE PHOENIX WAREHOUSE AND UNLOADED THE TO TES. I AM SENDING PHOTOGRAPHS OF THE SPILL SITE TO BREA.

column168: A DRIVER WAS HAULING FLU DUST FROM RAIL SIDING AT KIOWA, KS, TO LANDFILL AT USPCI LONE MOUNTAIN FACILITY. ON HIS PREVIOUS LOAD, THE DRIVER HAD A PROBL EM UNLOADING HIS TRAILER AND FOUND SOME FOREIGN OBJECTS  IN THE BOTTOM OF H IS TANK, WHERE THE FLU DUST IS UNLOADED BY AIR SLIDE THRU A PIPE. HE TRAVEL ED BACK TO KIOWA FOR THE NEXT LOAD. HE DECIDED TO PRESSURE UP ON HIS TANK T HINKING IT WAS EMPTY TO CHECK THE BOTTOM TO SEE IF THERE WERE ANY FOREIGN O BJECTS IN THE TANK. WHEN HE DID, THERE WAS SOME FLU DUST HUNG IN THE LINE, AND IT BLEW OUT ON THE GROUND. IMMEDIATELY, USPCI SENT REMEDIAL CREW AND CL EANED UP THE SPILL. LOCAL POLICE, REGION 6, AND KANSAS DEPT OF HEALTH WERE NOTIFIED. A MEETING WAS HELD BETWEEN MYSELF AND REPS OF THE USPCI ON THIS M ATTER. THE OUTCOME WAS FOR THE USPCI TO INSTRUCT THEIR FACILITY TO BE SURE TRAILERS WERE EMPTY WHEN COMPLETED DELIVERIES TO THEIR SITE ARE MADE. I HAV E THOROUGHLY INSTRUCTED OUR DRIVERS TO MAKE  SURE THE TRAILERS ARE EMPTY AN D CLEANED BEFORE THEY LEAVE THE DISPOSAL SITE AND NEVER LET ANY PART OF THE IR LOAD INTO THE ATMOSPHERE, EXCEPT AT THE DISPOSAL SITE.

column168: THIS 55-GALLON DRUM WAS ONE OF A SHIPMENT OF 10 DRUMS LOADED AT THE INDIANA POLIS TERMINAL. BEHIND THE DRUMS WAS A WOODEN SKID. A SMALL NAIL WAS PROTRU DING FROM THE LOWER EDGE OF THE WOODEN SKID. WHEN THE TRAILER WAS OPENED AT EVANSVILLE, CHLORINE ODOR WAS NOTICED. LOCAL FIRE DEPT WAS CALLED. IN CHEC KING THE FREIGHT BILLS, THEY NOTED THAT ANOTHER SHIPMENT OF 1 DRUM, ALSO FR OM OXFORD CHEMICAL, WAS COMPOUND CLEANING LIQUID HYDROFLUORIC ACID. (CORROS IVE MATERIAL NA1760). THERE WAS CONCERN THAT IF THE DRUM WITH ACID LEAKED AND CONTACTED THE LEAKI NG MATERIAL FROM A DRUM OF HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION, THERE COULD BE AN EXPLOSI ON OR FIRE. THE FIRE DEPT DECIDED ON A ONE BLOC EVACUATION. A SPILL RECOVER Y SERVICE WAS CALLED. OXFORD CHEMICAL WAS CONTACTED AND THEY ADVISED THAT T HE LOW PERCENTAGE OF CHLORINE ON THE LEAKING DRUM AND THE LOW PERCENTAGE OF ACID IN THE CLEANING COMPOUND LOWERED THE DANGER OF FIRE OR EXPLOSION TO A VERY LOW DEGREE. THEY ADVISED CLEARING A 100 FOOT AREA WAS SUFFICIENT. THE SPILL RECOVERY SERVICE UNLOADED THE TRAILER, USED SODA ASH TO NEUTRALIZ E ANY PROBLEM. THE DRUM OF CLEANING COMPOUND WAS NOT LEAKING. THE SMALL NAI L HAD PUNCTURED ONE OF THE HYPOCHLORITE  SOLUTION DRUMS. NO OTHER LEAK. OXF ORD ALSO ADVISED THAT THE SOLUTION WAS WATER SOLUBLE. THERE WAS NO CONTAMINATION OF OTHER FREIGHT. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PUT IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED TO OXFORD CHEMICAL COMPANY.

column168: THE RELEASE FROM THE CARGO TANK WAS DUE TO INCORRECT OPERATIONAL PROCEDURES BY THE DRIVER-OPERATOR. THE PERSONN EL WHO CLOSED THE MANHOLE ONLY LIGHTLY TIGHTENED THE WINGNUTS THAT HOLD THE MANHOLE CLOSED AND SECURE. THE DRIVER-OPERATOR WHO WAS RESPONSIBLE FOR THE SAFE OPERATION OF THE CARGO TANK DID NOT CHECK THAT THE WINGNUTS SECURING THE MANHOLE HAD BEEN ADEQUATELY TIGHTENED BEFORE LOADING THE CARGO TANK. SE VERAL HOURS AFTER LOADING, WHILE TAKING A REST BREAK ENROUTE, THE DRIVER-OP ERATOR NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE REAR MANHOLE AND AT THAT TIME ADEQUA TELY SECURED THE MANHOLE WINGNUTS WHICH STOPPED ALL LEAKING. APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF "COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID" LEAKED ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA AT THE TRUCK STOP WHERE THE CARGO TANK WAS PARKED. ALL MATERIAL THAT WAS RELEA SED WAS CONTAINED TO A SMALL AREA AT THE TRUCK STOP. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED WITH SAND, PLACED IN DRUMS AND TRANSPORTE D TO ENVIRONMENTAL TRANSPORTATION SERVICES, INC., 1813 SE 25TH ST, OKLAHOMA CITY, OK. THE SPILL AREA IN THE PARKING LOT WAS DECONTAMINATED.. DRIVER-OPERATOR PROCEDURES HAVE BEEN REVISED TO REQUIRE THAT ALL CARGO TANK CLOSURES ARE CHECKED AND ADEQUATELY SECURED BEFORE EACH LOADING.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 10:30 PM AT A MOBIL OWNED STATION AT 50 WEST JERICHO TURNPIKE, HUNTINGTON NEW YORK, TIM WHITLOCK SPILLED APPROXIMATELY 5-15 GALLONS OF UNLEADED GASOLINE.  HIS PAPER WORK (DRIVER DAILY SUMMARY) SHOWED THE PRESENCE OF AN UNLEAD TANK WITH A 20,000 GALLON CAPACITY. AFTER HE MEASURED THE PRODUCT, HE TOUGHT THE TANK COULD HOLD THE 4800 GALLONS OF UNLEAD THAT HE WAS TO DELIVER.  HE DROPPED THE 3600 COMPARTMENT AND WAS DROPPING THE 1200 COMPARTMENT WHEN HE SAW THAT THE TANK WAS FILLING UP.  HE THEN REALIZED THAT THE 20,000 GALLON CAPACITY WAS 2 10,00 GALLON TANKS.  HE SHUT OFF THE PUMP AND MOVED TO THE OTHER UNLEAD TANK. WITHOUT MEASUREING THE PRODUCT LEVEL IN THE 2ND UNLEAD TANK HE PROCEEDED TO DROP THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE 1200 COMPARTMENT.  5 TO 15 GALLONS SPILLED IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA AND THE DRIVER USED SPEEDY DRY TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT.

IN THE FUTURE WE WILL PROCEED THROUGH THIS AREA WITH EXTREME CAUTION AND REDUCE OUR SPEED SUBSTANTIALLY.

column42: HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S. OR ORM-E, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: WHILE OFFLOADING, TWO DRUMS WERE PUNCTURED WITH A FORKLIFT TINE.  ONE DRUM WAS ALSO LEAKING IN TRANSIT DUE TO METAL CORROSION.  THE TRAILER WAS A LINED TRAILER AND NO MATERIAL WAS RELEASED INTO THE ENVIRONMENT.  TRAILER FLOOR WAS CLEANED BY THE DISPOSAL FACILITY.

UPON OFF-LOADING AT TINKER, AFB, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT 27 OUT OF 61 DRUMS HAD LOOSE BUNGS, CROSS THREADED BUNGS, AND BUNGS WITH NO GASKETS.  THIS ALLOWED ABOUT 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO BE RELEASED.  MOST OF THE MATERIAL WAS STANDING ON TOP OF THE DRUMS, HOWEVER SOME MATERIAL DID REACH THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THIS WASNEUTRALIZED WITH VINEGAR.

OUR DRIVER WAS CLEARED FOR DILIVERY BY THE RECEIVER.  HE WAS DIRECTED TO UNLOAD INTO TOTE BINS LOCATED ON A RECEIVING DOCK.  HE WAS UNLOADING INTO THE FINNAL TOTE BIN WHEN HE NOTED MATERIAL LEAKING FROMA VALVE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE BIN.  HE STOPPED HIS DELIVERY AND ATTEMPTED TO CLOSE THE VALVE BUT THE CUSTOMER HAD PLACED THE TOTES TOO CLOSE TOGETHER ANDHE COULD NOT REACH THE VALVE.  HE LOCATED THE RECEIVER AND TOLD HIM OF THE PROBLEM AND THE TWO OF THEM WERE ABLE TO MOVE THE TOTE AND CLOSE THE VALVE.  THE RECEIVER HAS FAILED TO PROPERLY CLOSE THE VALVE PRIOR TO POSITIONING THE TOTES.  THE CUSTOMER TOOK CARE OF THE CLEAN UP AND DISPOSAL.

OUR DRIVER WAS CLEARED FOR UNLOADING AT DESTINATION.  HE CONNECTED THE HOSES AND ATTEMPTED TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE.  HE PRODUCT WAS NOT MOVING AND HE SHUT DOWN TO ATTEMPT TO DETERMINE THE PROBLEM.  HE THOUGHT THAT THERE WAS A RESTRICTION IN THE CUSTOMER'S LINE.  HE DID NOT PROPERLY BLEED THE PRESSURE FROM THE TRAILER AND WHEN HE DISCONNECTED THE VAPOR LINE HE WAS SPRAYED WITH VAPOR.  HE DID NOT HAVE ANY PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT ON AT THE TIME.  HE EXPERIENCED RESPIRATORY PROBLEMS AND WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL WHERE HE WAS ADMITTED FOR OBSERVATION.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: OUR DRIVER ARRIVED TO LOAD HIS TRAILER FOR DELIVERY.  HE WAS TO LOAD SOME PREMIUM AND ALSO SOME REGULAR GASOLINE.  HE ATTEMPTED TO LOAD THE PREMIUM FIRST BUT WAS NOT SUCCESSFUL.  HE THEREFORE SET THE METER TO LOAD THE REGULAR AND AFTER IT HAD STARTED HE LEFT TO FIND THE SHIPPER TO SEE WHAT WAS WRONG WITH THE PREMIUM.  BY THE TIME HE RETURNED HIS TRAILER WAS OVERFLOWING.  HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE FLOW AND NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED IN THE SHIPPER'S OIL WATER SEPARATOR.

ALL VALVES WERE SECURED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED AFTER APPLYING SEAL MPRR 01 434774 TO THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.

UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD MANAGER OF YARD AND INDUSTRY OPERATIONS, D. MANTOOTH, REPORTED THAT TANK CAR UCLX 30001 EMITTED A SMALL CLOUD OF VAPOR MIST FROM THE TOP WHILE IN BOWL TRACK 6.  UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD SPECIAL AGENT - HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, A. M. ROQUET, RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND REPLACED A FAILED RUPTURE DISC.  MS. ROQUET CHECKED ALL OTHER FITTINGS AND FOUND THEM TO BE TIGHT AND TANK CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.

WHILE INSPECTING TRAIN, VAPORS WERE NOTED COMING FROM GAUGE AREA OF CAR. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT HEAD PRESSURE GAUGE THAT IS CONNECTED BY 1/16 COPPER TUBING WAS LOOSE AT BASE FITTING.  FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED R-2 AIR UNLOADING VALVE WAS CRACKED OPEN.  GAUGE WAS SECURED AND VALVE CLOSED. UNABLE TO DETECT ANY VAPORS AT SITE AND HEAD PRESSURE GAUGE WAS AT ZERO READING. BOTH CREW MEMNBERS COMPLAINED OF DRY MOUTHS AND HEADACHE.  ON ARRIVAL AT LARAMIE, MR. CROZIER AND MR. SCHUND REQUESTED A MEDICAL CHECKUP.  MR HAROLD GOBLE, MANAGER TRAIN AND INDUSTRY OPERATIONS, TRANSPORTED BOTH CREW MEMBERS TO IVINSON HOSPITAL, LARAMIE, WYOMING.  AT 2115 HOURS, SAME DATE, BOTH CREW MEMBERS CHECKED OUT OKAY AND WERE RELEASED FOR DUTY.

column168: UP RAILROAD YARDMASTER, NORTH LITTLE ROCK, ARKANSAS, WAS ADVISED BY SWITCH CREW THAT TANK CAR CHVX 280985 WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF CAR.  CAR WAS SET OUT ON TRACK 309 FOR REPAIRS. UP SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, C. L. HILL, RESPONDED WITH THE FOLLOWING BEING DEVELOPED.  TWO OF EIGHT MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE OFF, THE REMAINING SIX BOLTS WERE LESS THAN FINGER TIGHT.  ALL BOLTS WERE SECURED BY AGENT HILL.

UP RAILROAD SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZMAT H W RODABOUGH, WAS NOTIFIED BY SCOTT WAGNER, THAT TRAILER REAZ 257037 WAS LEAKING. INSPECTION DETERMINED THE MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER WAS A BROWN LIQUID WITH NO ODOR AND NOT REACTIVE.  THE TRAILER WAS PLACARDED CORROSIVE.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE THE TRAILER AND AN EMPTY MOVED TO THE STORE HOUSE RAMP AT THE SALT LAKE SHOPS FOR TRANSLOADING. OPERATIONS COMMENCING AT THE RAMP AT 0845 HOURS, MAY 29, 1990.  ONE DRUM WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING AROUND THE BOTTOM.  THE DRUM HAD NOT BEEN DAMAGED AND NO OBVIOUS CAUSE WAS EVIDENT.  THE DRUM WAS TURNED OVER, THUS CAUSING THE LEAK TO STOP. THE LEAKING BARREL WAS REPAIRED AND RETURNED TO THE CONTAINER.  THE REMAINING CARGO WAS LOADED INTO THE ADDITIONAL TRAILER MPZ 250118 AND BOTH TRAILERS RELEASED TO ROADWAY AT 1125 HOURS.  THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO ANY OF THE CARGO AS A RESULT OF THIS OPERATION.

CREW ABOARD TRAIN DECY-24 NOTED ODOR COMING FROM UTLX 38674, RESIDUE, WHICH LAST CONTAINED ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, UN 1005. INSPECTION BY UP REVEALED THAT PACKING GLAND NUT ON GAUGING ROD WON ONE FULL TURN LOOSE.  MR. LOW TIGHTENED NUT WHICH MITIGATED LEAK.

STINE, WAS CONTACTED BY TOPEKA, KANSAS, YARDMASTER, BOB HOLLY, ADVISING THAT TRAIN LKF-96 HAD SET CAR GATX 97458 OUT ON TRACK 6 AND CREW REPORTED A STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA. ALSO, A HISSING SOUND COULD BE HEARD. MR. STINE'S INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE LEAK WAS FROM THE BASE OF THE "B" END LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE ACCOUNT THE SECUREMENT NUTS WERE LOOSE.  AFTER REMOVING THE VALVE WHEEL TO GAIN ACCESS, MR. STINE TIGHTENED NUTS WHICH SECURED THE LEAK.  CAR WAS RELEASED FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORTATION. MR. STINE NOTIFIED JOE RAZELAN AT CHEMTREC, TRAIN MANAGEMENT-OMAHA AND THE KANSAS DEPT. OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT.

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERILAS (SSA/HM) ARLA ROQUET WAS NOTIFIED OF TANKCAR UTLX 42104 LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM.  CAR WAS LOCATED AT PEPSICO SPUR TRACK.  SSA/HM ROQUET RESPONDED AND NOTED ONLY A SLIGHT MOISTRE AROUND THE BOTTOM FITTING.  PEPSICO WAS CONTACTED AND THEY ADVISED THAT THE ARLINGTON FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAM HAD RESPONDED AND TIGHTENED THE BOTTOM FITTING.  THIS EFFECTIVELY STOPPED THE LEAKAGE.  SSA/HM ROQUET CONTACTED ARLIGNTON POLICE DEPARTMENT FOR DETAILS OF INCIDENT.

THE DOLBY TRUCK DRIVEN BY MR. HAWK WAS MAKING A LEFT TURN ON TO RT. 22 WEST WHEN HE WAS STRUCK BY A EAST BOUND COAL TRUCK DRIVEN BY MR. RANDY COCHRAN OF LICHENFELS TRUCKING.  THE RESULT OF THE INPACT PUNCTURED THE DRIVER SIDE BULK DIESEL TANK, RESULTING IN A SPILL OF 25-30 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL. THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT WAS 11:40 AM WITH HEAVY FOG IN THE AREA.  MR. HAWK WAS TAKEN TO CONEMAUGH VALLEY HOSPITAL, JOHNSTOWN, PA WITH A HEAD LACERATION.  MR. COCHRAN WAS TAKEN TO INDIANA HOSPITAL, INDIANA, PA WITH A HAND INJURY.
